            <p>This entire collection has been digitally transferred. Access CDs are available for each interview and are located at the Tamiment Library.</p>
        </phystech>
        <bioghist id="ref20">
            <head>Historical/Biographical Note</head>
            <p>Peter Drucker has been an activist, historian and writer specializing in U.S. and international politics for over twenty years. He has written for publications such as the 
                <emph render="italic">Guardian</emph>, 
                <emph render="italic">International Viewpoint</emph>, 
                <emph render="italic">Shmate</emph> and 
                <emph render="italic">Gay Community News</emph>. He is currently an editor of the socialist journal 
                <emph render="italic">Against the Current</emph>.</p>
            <p>In 1994 Peter Drucker published the first full-length biography of Max Shachtman, a key figure in the 1960s civil rights, labor and peace movements. 
                <emph render="italic">Max Shachtman and His Left: A Socialist's Odyssey through the American Century</emph> draws on previously untapped archives and interviews to provide a comprehensive study of an important civil rights figure.</p>
        </bioghist>
        <acqinfo id="ref5">
            <head>Immediate Source of Acquisition note</head>
            <p>Peter Drucker donated these tapes to the Tamiment Library after the publication of his biography of Max Shachtman, 
                <emph render="italic">Max Shachtman and His Left: A Socialist's Odyssey through the American Century</emph> (1994). The accession number associated with this gift is 1950.081.</p>
        </acqinfo>
        <scopecontent id="ref1">
            <head>Scope and Contents note</head>
            <p>This collection consists of 8 interviews on 20 cassette tapes conducted by Drucker in 1986-1989. The oral histories of labor and civil rights activist Max Shactman and his associates were later used in Druckerâ€™s autobiography of Shachtman. The collection has been digitized, and access CDs are available for researcher use.</p>
        </scopecontent>
        <userestrict id="ref14">
            <head>Use Restrictions</head>
            <p>New York University holds any rights (including copyright and related rights to publicity and privacy) for the majority of the interviews in this collection. Unless otherwise noted, permission to publish or reproduce materials must be secured from the Tamiment Library. Interviews for which New York University does not hold rights are noted at the interview level.</p>
        </userestrict>
        <appraisal id="ref26">
            <head>Appraisal note</head>
            <p>No materials were separated from this collection.</p>
        </appraisal>
        <arrangement id="ref18">
            <head>Arrangement</head>
            <p>The interviews are arranged alphabetically by last name.</p>
        </arrangement>
        <accessrestrict id="ref15">
            <head>Access Restrictions</head>
            <p>Open for research without restrictions.</p>
        </accessrestrict>
